0.body: Welcome to the Manic Monolith: Do It Yourself book! This book will teach you the basics of the level editor, tricks and tips, and the use of ALL the objects in the game! note The book and the game are still in heavy developement, expect some things to be slightly out of date...
0.title: Introduction

1.body: One of the first thing you will have to learn is how to use the level editor UI, so this subchapter will walk you through all the stuff you need to know before you start using the level editor.
1.title: Editor UI

10.body: Another very important element of the level editor, the property editor allows you to change an object properties, like size, position, color, etc...
10.title: Property Editor

101.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. Its value will be where the Secret is in the level.
101.title: Positioning

102.body: This object defines Mart's spawn position in the level. It also defines where mart will appear after going through a Secret in the main level. caution This object is essential for a level, as levels without one will just refuse to load.
102.title: Spawnpoint

104.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. Its value will be where the Spawnpoint is in the level
104.title: Positioning

105.body: The Stud is the most important object in the entire level object, its the most basic bulding block one can use.
105.title: Stud

108.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Stud is in the level.
108.title: Positioning

11.body: Knowing all keybinds is not needed for using the level editor, but they can boost your productivity by a lot! Except the delete key you are going to use it sooner or later
11.title: Keybinds

111.body: Determines how transparent the object is, this value ranges from 0 to 1. 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
111.title: Transparency

112.body: An property which defines how reflective this object is. 1 is totally reflective, and 0 doesn't reflect anything at all.
112.title: Reflectance

113.body: Determines this object's shape. Those shapes are: Ball A spherical shape. Block A block shape. Cylinder A cylinder shape. Wedge A wedge shape with a slope on one side. Corner Wedge A wedge shape with slopes on two sides.
113.title: Shape

114.body: Sets if this object can collide with others, if an object is unanchored and has the Can Collide value set to false, the object will fall through the world as soon as the level is loaded.
114.title: Can Collide

115.body: A Vector3 value that determies the object's linear velocity. When either the X, Y or Z values are not 0, Mart's velocity will be affected by the object's velocity. The two most important interactions are as follow but others can happen depending on which values you input. Linear Velocity has the same direction as Mart's Velocity = More velocity WHILE standing on the object! Linear Velocity has the opposite direction as Mart's Velocity = Less velocity WHILE standing on the object!
115.title: Linear velocity

116.body: A Vector3 value that determies the object's angular velocity This one is a little more complicated, and there aren't visual examples of it in action! (yet) On top of that, Mart can't doesn't interact with Angular Velocity, only unanchored objects!
116.title: Angular Velocity

117.body: This object is a dynamic image which repeats in an object's surface. Not all objects can have Textures applied to them, however. For big levels, avoid using too many Textures, since they are heavier to render than Decals .
117.title: Texture

119.body: This property changes the color of the Texture, be wary that some colors wont actually change (eg.: black)
119.title: Color

12.body: Deletes the selected Object , be wary that some object can't be deleted.
12.title: Delete key

120.body: Determines how far the rendered texture is offset on the horizontal axis in studs.
120.title: Offset Studs U

121.body: Determines how far the rendered texture is offset on the horizontal axis in studs.
121.title: Offset Studs V

122.body: Sets the horizontal size, in studs, of the tiled image applied by the Texture.
122.title: Studs/Tile U

123.body: Sets the vertical size, in studs, of the tiled image applied by the Texture.
123.title: Studs/Tile V

124.body: A roblox Decal ID that the Texture will use.
124.title: Image ID

125.body: A number which ranges from 0 to 1, in which 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
125.title: Transparency

126.body: Determines the depth of the Texture relative to others. Example: Lets say that you have two Textures, and you want Decal A to be in front of Decal B, to solve that, simply set Decal A's Z Index to something higher than Decal B's Z Index.
126.title: Z Index

127.body: A property which defines what surface will this Decal be on.
127.title: Face

128.body: When you attempt to place a Texture, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will have a missing texture image applied to them when you hover your mouse over said objects, clicking on an elegible object will place the Texture in the surface your mouse was pointing at.
128.title: Placement

129.body: 2D Trigger is an object which changes the camera to 2D mode while Mart is touching it. Every 2D Trigger has a Vector3 Value child which holds the camera axis override
129.title: 2D Trigger

13.body: Undoes the last action, only some actions can be undone (this is going to change in the future)
13.title: Ctrl-Z key combination

130.body: All 2D Triggers have a Vector 3 Value child which determines the camera axis override. warning There are only two stable axis overrides, those are 1, 1, 0 or 0, 1, 1. All other axis override combinations are unstable. Although unstable, some combinations can have geniuine uses.
130.title: Remarks

133.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the 2D Trigger is in the level.
133.title: Positioning

134.body: This object cannot be placed, instead its a child of objects. This object has one purpose: hold a number value
134.title: Number Value

137.body: This object cannot be placed, instead its a child of objects. This object has one purpose: hold a vector3 value
137.title: Vector 3 Value

14.body: If an Object is selected, move the camera to that Object 's position (if it has one)
14.title: F key

15.body: Changes the position increment, in studs.
15.title: F4 Key

16.body: Changes the rotation increment, in degrees.
16.title: Ctrl-F4 key combination

17.body: If in position edit mode, pressing Q will change the positioning mode from local to world and vice-versa
17.title: Q key

18.body: THE most important feature in the entire level editor, how are you gonna make a level with no objects? Thats right, you can't! This chapter will have ALL the objects and their properties, this is intended to be used as a documentation for level creators.
18.title: Objects

19.body: An Attachment is used to store a position relative to its parent, for example, every Lap 2 object will have an Attachment as its child, said attachment points to the position Mart is going to be teleported when he touches the Lap 2 object.
19.title: Attachment

2.body: One of the core elements of the UI, its simple, but you will be using this very often. Its composed of various buttons each with a different function.
2.breadcrumbs: Introduction » Editor UI » The options bar
2.title: The options bar

21.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. Its value will be where the Attachment is relative to its parent
21.title: Positioning

22.body: When you attempt to place an Attachment in the level, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will gain a orange-ish outline on them, click on an elegible object and the attachment will be placed as a child of that object.
22.title: Placing

23.body: Birby is an enemy with no behaviour, its just static object that can be killed.
23.title: Birby

25.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. Its value is simply where Birby is in the level.
25.title: Positioning

26.body: Its a solid block which breaks when Mart collides with it at reasonably slow speeds. Grabbing breaks them, so does groundpounding/divebombing on them.
26.title: Breakable Block (weak)

28.body: Determines this object's size note The block's durability won't change with size! Its best to just have a long sequence of individual breakable blocks if you thought of doing that!
28.title: Size

29.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Breakable Block (weak) is in the level
29.title: Positioning

3.body: Its the ">" button, it just hides the options bar so that you can have more screen space.
3.title: Hide button

32.body: An property which defines how reflective this object is. 1 is totally reflective, and 0 doesn't reflect anything at all.
32.title: Reflectance

33.body: Determines this object's shape. Those shapes are: Ball A spherical shape. Block A block shape. Cylinder A cylinder shape. Wedge A wedge shape with a slope on one side. Corner Wedge A wedge shape with slopes on two sides.
33.title: Shape

36.title: Angular Velocity

37.body: Its a solid block which breaks when Mart collides with it at high speeds. Groundpounds/divebombs dont break this block unless Mart is going past a certain vertical speed.
37.title: Breakable Block (strong)

39.body: Determines this object's size note The block's durability won't change with size! Its best to just have a long sequence of individual breakable blocks if you thought of doing that!
39.title: Size

4.body: When pressed it teleports you to the main game where your level is instantly loaded after the loading screen finishes You can't playtest your level if your level settings are invalid If you haven't saved your level, the playtest button will give you a warning and do nothing.
4.title: Playtest

48.body: Its a collectible which increases the player's score then they touch Mart.
48.title: Coin

5.body: Another very important element of the level editor, when pressed, a vertical bar will appear at the left side of the screen, displaying all of the objects you can place in a level Clicking on an object puts it in your mouse cursor, from there, drag your mouse at the place you want to put the object an simply click with the left mouse button, 🎉 You have placed your first object!
5.title: Objects

50.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Coin is in the level
50.title: Positioning

51.body: Determines how transparent the object is, this value ranges from 0 to 1. 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
51.title: Transparency

52.body: Its a collectible which increases the player's score then they touch Mart. This object behaves almost identically to the Coin , but this one can only be collected during Manic Mania.
52.title: Coin (Manic Mania)

54.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Coin (Manic Mania) is in the level
54.title: Positioning

55.body: Determines how transparent the object is, this value ranges from 0 to 1. 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
55.title: Transparency

56.body: This object is a static image which is stretched into an object's surface. Not all objects can have Decals applied to them, however. For big levels, try to use Decals when possible instead of Textures , since its more lightweight on the player's device.
56.title: Decal

58.body: Determines this object's color. Be wary that some colors wont actually change (eg.: black)
58.title: Color

59.body: A roblox Decal ID that the Decal will use.
59.title: Image ID

6.body: Its where you tweak your level behavior, like the amount of points needed for each rank, level track ID, level name ETC...
6.title: Level Settings

60.body: Determines how transparent the object is, this value ranges from 0 to 1. 1 is fully transparent while 0 is fully opaque
60.title: Transparency

61.title: Z Index

62.title: Face

63.body: When you attempt to place a Decal, your mouse icon will change and elegible objects will have a missing texture decal applied to them when you hover your mouse over said objects, clicking on an elegible object will place the decal in the surface your mouse was pointing at.
63.title: Placement

64.body: This object ends the level when touched during Manic Mania. caution An Escape object is essential for a level, as there is no way of finishing a level (successfully) without it!
64.title: Escape

66.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Escape object is in the level
66.title: Positioning

68.body: The Lap 2 object teleports Mart to where its Attachment child points to. important A Lap 2 object is essential for a level, since the player can't get a P rank without it.
68.title: Lap 2

69.body: This object has an Attachment as a child, the Attachment 's position will be used to determine where Mart will get teleported after starting Lap 2
69.title: Remarks

7.body: When clicked, an view of all the objects in the current level will show in a tree like hierarchy. Clicking on an object will select it.
7.title: Object Tree

71.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Lap 2 object is in the level
71.title: Positioning

73.body: This object starts Manic Mania when touched, this object also gives points and a combo boost when touched. caution A Manic Mania Cube object is essential for a level since there is no way of triggering Manic Mania without one of those.
73.breadcrumbs: Objects » Manic Mania Cube » Manic Mania Cube
73.title: Manic Mania Cube

75.title: Positioning

76.body: This object inherits all the properties from the Stud object, but this one can only collide with Mart during Manic Mania.

79.body: This property can only be edited with the position/rotation handle. The value corresponds to where the Manic Mania Stud (collide) is in the level.
79.title: Positioning

8.body: Allows you to save, load and erase your levels. You can also: Save a level as new level (you won't overwrite any levels you already got) Load a new empty level
8.title: Save/Load Level

9.body: It changes the current view of your level when clicked. The order goes by (it loops back to the first view mode) Level Mode: Its the default mode, you can only see and edit the main world (where Mart spawns) Secret 1-3 Mode: All those are like the Level Mode, but you can only see and edit their respective secrets.

98.body: An secret object has a Number Value as it child. When Mart touches this object, he gets teleported into the secret tied with the Number Value 's Value property. If mart touches this object while already in a secret, he gets sent back to the secret he first went through.
98.title: Secret

99.body: This object has a Number Value as its child, this Number Value , stores a value ranging from 1 to 3, this value must be unique between all secrets in the main level.
99.title: Remarks
